00:06:11.610 --> 00:06:19.400
From 1920-1930 the population
of Mexico was on the move.

00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:22.490
Hundreds of thousands of
Mexicans took to the railroads

00:06:22.490 --> 00:06:24.160
and the highways to migrate

00:06:24.160 --> 00:06:27.280
across the northern border
to the United States.

00:06:27.280 --> 00:06:31.400 position:56%
This migratory flow was so
enormous that the Mexican population

00:06:31.400 --> 00:06:34.730
in the United States -- the
Mexican origin population --

00:06:34.730 --> 00:06:39.650
doubled from about 500,000 to
about a little over 1 million.

00:06:39.650 --> 00:06:42.160
There were several causes for this.

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:47.450
One of them was the 1910-1920
Mexican Revolution which sort

00:06:47.450 --> 00:06:50.010
of decimated the countryside
and forced a lot

00:06:50.010 --> 00:06:55.100
of people off their lands in
search of jobs and safety.

00:06:55.100 --> 00:06:57.150
There was also population growth,

00:06:57.150 --> 00:07:00.570
especially in the most
populated central part of Mexico.

00:07:00.570 --> 00:07:02.910
There was a decline in
agricultural production.

00:07:02.910 --> 00:07:04.810
Some environmental causes.

00:07:04.810 --> 00:07:07.080
There were low wages in Mexico.

00:07:07.080 --> 00:07:10.380
There were new transportation
networks, highways and railroads

00:07:10.380 --> 00:07:13.260
that offered quicker
and easier ways to get

00:07:13.260 --> 00:07:14.860
from Mexico to the United States.

00:07:14.860 --> 00:07:18.530
And then in the United States
there were higher wages

00:07:18.530 --> 00:07:21.690
and there were numerous
new jobs available

00:07:21.690 --> 00:07:23.680
to Mexican migrants in particular.

00:07:23.680 --> 00:07:26.050
Especially in agriculture.

00:07:26.050 --> 00:07:28.620
So the cotton fields
and the sugar beet farms

00:07:28.620 --> 00:07:30.740
of the Southwest and Midwest.

00:07:30.740 --> 00:07:32.480
And in industry.

00:07:32.480 --> 00:07:35.050 position:56%
Steel factories, meatpacking plants.

00:07:35.050 --> 00:07:39.340
And this was particularly
true in cities in the Midwest

00:07:39.340 --> 00:07:42.650
and also in the US Southwest.

00:07:42.650 --> 00:07:47.720
There was another cause though of
Mexican migration during the 1920's

00:07:47.720 --> 00:07:49.950
and this one is a little
bit lesser known.

00:07:49.950 --> 00:07:51.830
And this is the topic
that I work on.

00:07:51.830 --> 00:07:56.390
It's a war now called
the Cristero War.

00:07:56.390 --> 00:07:59.760
This was a very violent,
blood conflict

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:04.950
between Mexican Catholic partisans
and the Mexican government,

00:08:04.950 --> 00:08:08.810
which was at the time, as a
result of the Mexican Revolution,

00:08:08.810 --> 00:08:12.440
enacting very strict
anti-clerical legislations.

00:08:12.440 --> 00:08:14.030
Legislation that forbade people

00:08:14.030 --> 00:08:18.590
from essentially practicing
their Catholic faith in public.

00:08:18.590 --> 00:08:20.930
It sound strange because
as you probably know,

00:08:20.930 --> 00:08:24.620
Mexico is a vast majority
Catholic country.

00:08:24.620 --> 00:08:27.240
But it's also a country where the
church and state had struggled

00:08:27.240 --> 00:08:29.740
for really centuries
up until this time.

00:08:29.740 --> 00:08:33.580
So this was an outbreak
of church state violence.

00:08:33.580 --> 00:08:38.570
During the war, these catholic
partisans became militant

00:08:38.570 --> 00:08:42.840
and they went to battle
against the federal government.

00:08:42.840 --> 00:08:47.490
You know, armed with rifles but
also with crosses and scapulars

00:08:47.490 --> 00:08:48.900
and religious medallions.

00:08:48.900 --> 00:08:52.590
And they launched themselves
into battle with the battle cry

00:08:52.590 --> 00:08:56.120
of viva Cristo ray, or
"Long live Christ the king."

00:08:56.120 --> 00:08:58.660
And that's why they're
known as Cristeros,

00:08:58.660 --> 00:09:01.500
or I guess it would be
Christers in English,

00:09:01.500 --> 00:09:03.260
which doesn't sound very good.

00:09:03.260 --> 00:09:06.560
They believed that they
were in a holy war and that

00:09:06.560 --> 00:09:09.920
when they died they would become
martyrs, Catholic martyrs.

00:09:09.920 --> 00:09:15.240
And so my book, which actually
somehow you got an old title

00:09:15.240 --> 00:09:18.500
for my book, so I'll give you
the new title, the real title.

00:09:18.500 --> 00:09:19.800
&gt;&gt; Jason Steinhauer: I'm sorry.

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:21.100
&gt;&gt; Julia Young: No, no, no.

00:09:21.100 --> 00:09:22.400
It's floating out there somewhere.

00:09:22.400 --> 00:09:23.940
It's called Mexican
Exodus: Emigrants,

00:09:23.940 --> 00:09:26.220
Exiles and Refugees
of the Cristero War.

00:09:26.220 --> 00:09:27.630
A little bit simpler.

00:09:27.630 --> 00:09:32.890
So my book examines the ways that
this Mexican migration overlapped

00:09:32.890 --> 00:09:35.760
with this religions
conflict that was going on.

00:09:35.760 --> 00:09:40.360
And I find that the war actually
had a really significant impact

00:09:40.360 --> 00:09:42.640
on this migrant community.

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:46.790
Partly it was just
coincidence, the geographic

00:09:46.790 --> 00:09:48.220
and chronological coincidence.

00:09:48.220 --> 00:09:50.860
The war happened at the same time
that this migration was happening.

00:09:50.860 --> 00:09:53.240
And it happened in the
same place that most

00:09:53.240 --> 00:09:55.810
of the migrants were
leaving: west/central Mexico.

00:09:55.810 --> 00:09:57.900
The states -- for those
of you who know Mexico,

00:09:57.900 --> 00:10:00.240
if you drew a big circle
around the city of Guadalajara,

00:10:00.240 --> 00:10:02.880
that would be the region.

00:10:02.880 --> 00:10:08.830
So it also impacted migration
in some more specific ways.

00:10:08.830 --> 00:10:12.110
It created a refugee flow.

00:10:12.110 --> 00:10:17.140
During the war, the Catholic
clergy, so priests, nuns, bishops,

00:10:17.140 --> 00:10:20.480
were often actively persecuted
by the Mexican government.

00:10:20.480 --> 00:10:23.480
And so they either
were forced into exile

00:10:23.480 --> 00:10:25.530
or sought refuge in
the United States.

00:10:25.530 --> 00:10:28.180
So there were about 2,000
members of the Catholic clergy

00:10:28.180 --> 00:10:30.700
that migrated to the United States.

00:10:30.700 --> 00:10:34.210
There was also a flow of political
exiles, Catholic activists who felt

00:10:34.210 --> 00:10:38.230
that they had to leave the country
because they were in danger.

00:10:38.230 --> 00:10:43.530
And these groups joined the
existing flow of economic emigrants

00:10:43.530 --> 00:10:45.120
that were leaving the area already.

00:10:45.120 --> 00:10:49.100
That left the area before the
war started and after it went on.

00:10:49.100 --> 00:10:53.850
And it's this last group,
the sort of economic --

00:10:53.850 --> 00:10:55.870
what we think of as
economic migrants --

00:10:55.870 --> 00:10:58.980
that I think is of interest
for this particular discussion.

00:10:58.980 --> 00:11:01.820
I'll bring up two cases in
particular very quickly.

00:11:01.820 --> 00:11:05.050
One is a man named Miguel Vanegas.

00:11:05.050 --> 00:11:07.890
I think these cases are sort of
indicative of the larger group

00:11:07.890 --> 00:11:10.060
of people I'm talking about.

00:11:10.060 --> 00:11:11.360
So Miguel Vanegas was the owner

00:11:11.360 --> 00:11:13.400
of a general store in
the state of Jalisco.

00:11:13.400 --> 00:11:17.630
Its capital city is
Guadalajara, Cristero hotbed.

00:11:17.630 --> 00:11:20.250
He and his family were
strong Cristero supporters.

00:11:20.250 --> 00:11:23.350
His brother joined the
Cristero troops and eventually,

00:11:23.350 --> 00:11:25.300
ultimately died in the conflict,

00:11:25.300 --> 00:11:27.300
was considered a martyr
within the family.

00:11:27.300 --> 00:11:31.740
And he himself was also
a Cristero supporter.

00:11:31.740 --> 00:11:37.610
When federal troops came to his
town, they were aware of his

00:11:37.610 --> 00:11:38.910
and his family's sympathies.

00:11:38.910 --> 00:11:43.410
And they let it be known that
he better leave the state

00:11:43.410 --> 00:11:46.450
or he would potentially be killed.

00:11:46.450 --> 00:11:50.120
So he went into hiding and
ultimately he went to Los Angeles

00:11:50.120 --> 00:11:52.670
where he started a
grocery store very similar

00:11:52.670 --> 00:11:56.240
to his general store
back home in Jalisco.

00:11:56.240 --> 00:12:00.290
In Los Angeles, I think by the time
he left Mexico he had four children

00:12:00.290 --> 00:12:02.860
and ultimately he and his
wife would have 10 children.

00:12:02.860 --> 00:12:05.400
He raised all of these 10
children in Los Angeles.

00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:07.850
The grocery store supported
the family.

00:12:07.850 --> 00:12:11.180
And they stayed in the United
States after the war ended.

00:12:11.180 --> 00:12:14.100
In fact, the descendants of
Miguel Vanegas still live

00:12:14.100 --> 00:12:16.730
in Los Angeles to this day.

00:12:16.730 --> 00:12:20.840
But he raised his children
to be good, devoted Catholics

00:12:20.840 --> 00:12:26.730
and to remember and support this
Cristero cause back home in Mexico.

00:12:26.730 --> 00:12:29.270
He and his family participated

00:12:29.270 --> 00:12:34.150
in anti-government Catholic
activism from Los Angeles.

00:12:34.150 --> 00:12:37.270
And they continued to view
themselves as Cristero supporters,

00:12:37.270 --> 00:12:39.590
both during the 1920's
and afterwards.

00:12:39.590 --> 00:12:43.730
Another quick case is the case of
Saradino Lopez, also from the state

00:12:43.730 --> 00:12:45.180
of -- actually from
the state of Michoacan

00:12:45.180 --> 00:12:47.000
but lived in the state of Jalisco.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:49.370
He was a journalist who
wrote critical articles

00:12:49.370 --> 00:12:55.230
about the Mexican government while
the Cristero war was going on.

00:12:55.230 --> 00:12:57.800
He also was told that
he better leave

00:12:57.800 --> 00:12:59.390
or he would find himself in danger.

00:12:59.390 --> 00:13:04.390
And so he had friends who
were living outside of Chicago

00:13:04.390 --> 00:13:06.540
in the growing Mexican
community outside Chicago.

00:13:06.540 --> 00:13:08.150
And they told him,
"Well, come on over here.

00:13:08.150 --> 00:13:10.660
There are jobs and you
can make a new home here."

00:13:10.660 --> 00:13:13.280
So he came to Chicago,
he made it his home.

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:18.030
And he started a newspaper just
like the one he had run in Mexico.

00:13:18.030 --> 00:13:20.660
And that newspaper was critical
of the Mexican government

00:13:20.660 --> 00:13:22.850
and it actually was a tool

00:13:22.850 --> 00:13:26.010
that rallied Cristero
support in the United States.

00:13:26.010 --> 00:13:28.400
Through the newspaper he
got people to donate funds

00:13:28.400 --> 00:13:31.810
which he then sent back to
the Cristero troops in Mexico.

00:13:31.810 --> 00:13:35.940
But he too and his family
stayed in Chicago after the war,

00:13:35.940 --> 00:13:38.100
made a living there,
raised children there.

00:13:38.100 --> 00:13:41.160
One of his sons became a Catholic
priest who eventually went back

00:13:41.160 --> 00:13:47.080
to Mexico when that
was legal once again.

00:13:47.080 --> 00:13:49.630
And so these are migrants.

00:13:49.630 --> 00:13:51.740
I know of many cases
of them but don't have

00:13:51.740 --> 00:13:53.540
as many stories like this.

00:13:53.540 --> 00:13:57.950
But there were thousands of
people like this who left

00:13:57.950 --> 00:14:00.820
because of the war
for political reasons,

00:14:00.820 --> 00:14:02.550
but also for economic reasons.

00:14:02.550 --> 00:14:05.080
They couldn't maintain
their businesses

00:14:05.080 --> 00:14:07.590
in Mexico during this conflict.

00:14:07.590 --> 00:14:10.680
And so when they relocated
to the United States,

00:14:10.680 --> 00:14:14.630 position:56%
became business people in the United
States and made a living there.

00:14:14.630 --> 00:14:19.270
So how do we classify
these types of migrants?

00:14:19.270 --> 00:14:23.320
Typically, Mexican migrants
from this period are thought

00:14:23.320 --> 00:14:26.200
of as labor migrants,
as economic migrants.

00:14:26.200 --> 00:14:30.140
And we as historians have
talked about them in terms

00:14:30.140 --> 00:14:34.770 position:56%
of their economic motivations, their
economic interests and their labor.

00:14:34.770 --> 00:14:39.400
And what I argue in my book, I call
this group the Cristero diaspora.

00:14:39.400 --> 00:14:42.470
A scattered group of people

00:14:42.470 --> 00:14:45.930
that supported the Cristero
cause from the United States.

00:14:45.930 --> 00:14:47.480
And what I argue in my book is

00:14:47.480 --> 00:14:51.970
that this story tells us something
important about Mexican migrants.

00:14:51.970 --> 00:14:55.440
It tells us that Mexican
migrants were political actors.

00:14:55.440 --> 00:14:58.720
That they rallied around
causes within their homeland.

00:14:58.720 --> 00:15:00.670 position:56%
That they had religious motivations.

00:15:00.670 --> 00:15:04.170 position:56%
And by the way, not all of Mexican
migrants supported the Cristero War.

00:15:04.170 --> 00:15:06.630
Lots of them actually supported
the Mexican government.

00:15:06.630 --> 00:15:09.720
And these people fought with
each other in the United States.

00:15:09.720 --> 00:15:16.310
So Mexican migrants, you know,
need to be viewed outside

00:15:16.310 --> 00:15:21.260
of this limiting lens of
economic or labor migration,

00:15:21.260 --> 00:15:24.350
is my argument both
in the book and here.

00:15:24.350 --> 00:15:28.370
And I think it helps us think
about something that we'll talk

00:15:28.370 --> 00:15:30.890
about a little bit more
today, which is, you know,

00:15:30.890 --> 00:15:34.330
how do these categories that we
try to stuff migrants into --

00:15:34.330 --> 00:15:35.960
you know, are you an
economic migrant?

00:15:35.960 --> 00:15:37.260
Are you a refugee?

00:15:37.260 --> 00:15:39.600
Are you a political exile?

00:15:39.600 --> 00:15:42.810
How can we blur these categories
in creative ways to think

00:15:42.810 --> 00:15:44.670
about migrants differently?

00:15:44.670 --> 00:15:47.200
So I'll stop there.

