&gt;&gt; Ivan Chaar-Lopez: Thank you.

00:15:48.700 --> 00:15:51.320
So thank you all for coming.

00:15:51.320 --> 00:15:56.550
It's exciting to talk about my
project in large part because I'm

00:15:56.550 --> 00:15:59.200
in the process of research
and writing it.

00:15:59.200 --> 00:16:03.130
So I'm at a different
stage than my peers.

00:16:03.130 --> 00:16:06.550
And right now my dissertation
project is titled Drone Techno

00:16:06.550 --> 00:16:08.100
Politics: A History

00:16:08.100 --> 00:16:10.640
of the Datafication of
the US-Mexico Border.

00:16:10.640 --> 00:16:14.050
And it traces the long and
complicated trajectories

00:16:14.050 --> 00:16:18.350
of databases and computers
as instruments

00:16:18.350 --> 00:16:22.150
of empires since the 1960's.

00:16:22.150 --> 00:16:27.130
Databases and computers I think
help us understand how drones later

00:16:27.130 --> 00:16:31.840
on in the 2000's become
the technological choice

00:16:31.840 --> 00:16:35.940
for border surveillance operations.

00:16:35.940 --> 00:16:40.470
Now contemporary debates, as
Jason mentioned, demonstrate --

00:16:40.470 --> 00:16:44.120
contemporary debates about the
border demonstrate a pressing need

00:16:44.120 --> 00:16:52.060
to take a critical look into what
people call technological fixes,

00:16:52.060 --> 00:16:54.850
or so-called technological fixes.

00:16:54.850 --> 00:16:59.760
Doing so sheds light on how the
border operates as a laboratory

00:16:59.760 --> 00:17:04.010
for modes of governing and
administering populations.

00:17:04.010 --> 00:17:06.180
More precisely, the border I think

00:17:06.180 --> 00:17:09.320
and I argue throughout
my project is a zone

00:17:09.320 --> 00:17:13.190
where noncitizens become
expendable subjects

00:17:13.190 --> 00:17:16.800
in the experimentation
of biopolitics.

00:17:16.800 --> 00:17:19.580
My goal in the end
is to contextualize

00:17:19.580 --> 00:17:23.130
and interrogate the
techno political fixation

00:17:23.130 --> 00:17:25.460
on data, both big and small.

00:17:25.460 --> 00:17:31.210
As well as on digital technologies
as end-all, solve-all solutions

00:17:31.210 --> 00:17:34.440
to border policing and
immigration enforcement.

00:17:34.440 --> 00:17:38.070
To do this I don't only
inquire how computers,

00:17:38.070 --> 00:17:40.280
databases and drones are imagined.

00:17:40.280 --> 00:17:44.210
I also open the technological
black box if you will,

00:17:44.210 --> 00:17:47.000
to examine its internal operations.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:50.400
So what do technologies
do, how do they do it?

00:17:50.400 --> 00:17:55.000
What are their methods
for acting upon the world?

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:58.650
The way that I'm going about my
project right now is writing what I

00:17:58.650 --> 00:18:03.330
call historical snapshots of
specific technological fixes,

00:18:03.330 --> 00:18:07.550
or that question specific
technological fixes.

00:18:07.550 --> 00:18:10.450
So the study begins with
a database system known

00:18:10.450 --> 00:18:14.690
as the Alien Documentation
Identification

00:18:14.690 --> 00:18:16.260
and Telecommunication System.

00:18:16.260 --> 00:18:18.880
It's a mouthful so I say it slowly.

00:18:18.880 --> 00:18:24.900
But ADITS, as it was known, created
in the 1970's, was at the center

00:18:24.900 --> 00:18:28.300
of INS, or immigration
naturalization service.

00:18:28.300 --> 00:18:33.140
The center of INS is the
process of automation.

00:18:33.140 --> 00:18:37.770
It was really a very
important project.

00:18:37.770 --> 00:18:43.880
And I look into this system
from 1975 and then I finish

00:18:43.880 --> 00:18:50.770
with the Arizona Border Control
Initiative of 2004-2005 which is --

00:18:50.770 --> 00:18:57.480 position:56%
what I found so far is the first use
of drones in the US-Mexico border.

00:18:57.480 --> 00:19:02.330
Now each snapshot follows a variety
of actors in federal government,

00:19:02.330 --> 00:19:05.380 position:56%
private industry, academic research.

00:19:05.380 --> 00:19:11.130
It also looks into
journalism and activism to try

00:19:11.130 --> 00:19:18.850 position:56%
to trace the different types of
state work that computers, databases

00:19:18.850 --> 00:19:21.780
and drones are imagined to perform.

00:19:21.780 --> 00:19:25.020
And just to give you a little
sense of what I'm talking about,

00:19:25.020 --> 00:19:29.280
which might sound a little bit
abstract, I have a few images

00:19:29.280 --> 00:19:30.850
that I would like to share.

00:19:30.850 --> 00:19:35.230
So this is just an aerial
take of the Santa Fe bridge.

00:19:35.230 --> 00:19:39.980
This is the port of entry in
