00:22:52.470 --> 00:22:54.670
of cases that I have collected.

00:22:54.670 --> 00:22:59.040
And then I'll talk a little
bit about the larger categories

00:22:59.040 --> 00:23:02.820
that I think these cases
are representative of.

00:23:02.820 --> 00:23:09.160 position:56%
So in 2006 a man from Nigeria sought
asylum in Canada on the grounds

00:23:09.160 --> 00:23:11.970
that the Nigerian state
did not offer protection

00:23:11.970 --> 00:23:15.160
to the particular social
group that he belonged to:

00:23:15.160 --> 00:23:17.970
persons accused of witchcraft.

00:23:17.970 --> 00:23:22.160
The immigration and refugee board
of Canada rejected his claim

00:23:22.160 --> 00:23:26.920
on the grounds that the documentary
evidence in this situation --

00:23:26.920 --> 00:23:32.580
country conditions report -- showed
that "despite apathy and reluctance

00:23:32.580 --> 00:23:36.090
on the part of the police, people
have been arrested by the police

00:23:36.090 --> 00:23:39.140
and convicted before judges."

00:23:39.140 --> 00:23:41.140
The claim was denied.

00:23:41.140 --> 00:23:44.890
The asylum seeker appealed to
the federal court of Canada

00:23:44.890 --> 00:23:47.530
for a judicial review of his case.

00:23:47.530 --> 00:23:51.550
The judge noted that the board
had relied on documentary evidence

00:23:51.550 --> 00:23:54.710
which dealt with people convicted
for practicing witchcraft.

00:23:54.710 --> 00:24:00.560
I have noted the report "could
not constitute state protection

00:24:00.560 --> 00:24:03.640
of persons wrongly
accused of witchcraft."

00:24:03.640 --> 00:24:09.660
The asylum seeker was granted
a new hearing in this case.

00:24:09.660 --> 00:24:13.830
In 2012, Namibian asylum
seekers, a mother

00:24:13.830 --> 00:24:16.490
and her minor son, came to Canada.

00:24:16.490 --> 00:24:18.670
They made the argument
that they belonged

00:24:18.670 --> 00:24:23.670
to a particular social group at
risk for harm from witchcraft.

00:24:23.670 --> 00:24:27.460
The mother explained that her
son faced a high risk of death

00:24:27.460 --> 00:24:29.970
from witch doctors in Namibia.

00:24:29.970 --> 00:24:33.110
The death of her parents had
been linked to witchcraft.

00:24:33.110 --> 00:24:36.770
Competing for her inheritance,
her relatives had cursed her

00:24:36.770 --> 00:24:39.320
and said she would
die like her parents.

00:24:39.320 --> 00:24:45.120
Her brothers had respectively found
a big snake on their front porch

00:24:45.120 --> 00:24:47.700
and another one found
a bowl of blood

00:24:47.700 --> 00:24:50.210
with an owl on his front porch.

00:24:50.210 --> 00:24:56.040
They took this as evidence of black
magic being practiced against them.

00:24:56.040 --> 00:24:59.270
The asylum seeker said that
he'd never sought out protection

00:24:59.270 --> 00:25:02.250
from state authorities
because her family was going

00:25:02.250 --> 00:25:04.040
through witchcraft problems.

00:25:04.040 --> 00:25:09.990
And as she explained "the state
cannot protect us from witchcraft."

00:25:09.990 --> 00:25:13.570
The immigration and refugee
board rejected her claim,

00:25:13.570 --> 00:25:15.310 position:56%
saying that the harm that she feared

00:25:15.310 --> 00:25:19.050
over her inheritance was
definitely a family matter.

00:25:19.050 --> 00:25:21.390
It rejected the claim that her son,

00:25:21.390 --> 00:25:25.880 position:56%
who suffered from a condition that's
actually redacted in the decision,

00:25:25.880 --> 00:25:29.510
did not face from witch doctors.

00:25:29.510 --> 00:25:34.290
People suffering from his condition
were not killed in Namibia.

00:25:34.290 --> 00:25:38.820 position:56%
And they also rejected her claim
that the state offered no protection

00:25:38.820 --> 00:25:41.590
from witchcraft and
cited a range of evidence

00:25:41.590 --> 00:25:46.370 position:56%
that Namibia was a democratic state.

00:25:46.370 --> 00:25:49.960
So these cases are
exemplars of the archive

00:25:49.960 --> 00:25:53.830
of nearly 40 cases
that I put together.

00:25:53.830 --> 00:25:57.950
And what I'm examining is cases
in which African asylum seekers

00:25:57.950 --> 00:26:02.210
who are coming from Anglophone
Africa to commonwealth countries.

00:26:02.210 --> 00:26:05.880
To Canada, the UK and Australia.

00:26:05.880 --> 00:26:09.290
Alleged that being accused
of witchcraft or targeted

00:26:09.290 --> 00:26:13.870 position:56%
with witchcraft makes them a member
of a particular social group subject

00:26:13.870 --> 00:26:17.550
to persecution and eligible
for refugee protection.

00:26:17.550 --> 00:26:20.330
So I think that these
cases offer avenues

00:26:20.330 --> 00:26:24.810
to explore some key categories
in refugee status determination.

00:26:24.810 --> 00:26:29.160
But also in the legal history
of witchcraft and the management

00:26:29.160 --> 00:26:33.450
of witchcraft related crime
on the African continent.

00:26:33.450 --> 00:26:36.290
So when I am talking about
witchcraft in these cases,

00:26:36.290 --> 00:26:41.530
I'm talking about an embodied
capacity, an object or a practice

00:26:41.530 --> 00:26:48.440 position:56%
that mobilizes an invisible,
malevolent power to harm the person,

00:26:48.440 --> 00:26:52.790
property, psyche or kin of another.

00:26:52.790 --> 00:26:58.120 position:56%
Asylum seekers have to show that the
state doesn't offer protection form

00:26:58.120 --> 00:27:01.480
the kind of violence that they
allege that they have suffered

00:27:01.480 --> 00:27:06.390
or that they will suffer if they
return to their country of origin.

00:27:06.390 --> 00:27:10.440
So part of my project is to
inquire into the deep jurisprudence

00:27:10.440 --> 00:27:14.210
about witchcraft on
the African continent,

00:27:14.210 --> 00:27:19.240
and to establish a history to
these claims of the absence

00:27:19.240 --> 00:27:23.190
of state protection from
witchcraft-driven violence.

00:27:23.190 --> 00:27:27.160
Asylum seekers also have to show
that they meet one of the criteria

00:27:27.160 --> 00:27:29.160
for refugee status that's laid

00:27:29.160 --> 00:27:32.710
out in the 1951 UN
convention on refugees.

00:27:32.710 --> 00:27:36.730
So these criteria are race,
religion, political opinion,

00:27:36.730 --> 00:27:41.490 position:56%
nationality and of course membership
of a particular social group.

00:27:41.490 --> 00:27:45.970
And this convention
is really the lynchpin

00:27:45.970 --> 00:27:49.440
of the refugee status
determination process.

00:27:49.440 --> 00:27:54.100
So my project is taking
witchcraft-based asylum cases

00:27:54.100 --> 00:27:58.000
as an avenue through which
to explore the expansion

00:27:58.000 --> 00:27:59.670
of the social group criteria.

00:27:59.670 --> 00:28:02.680
And this is the only
criterion of the UN convention

00:28:02.680 --> 00:28:05.000
that has been expanding
in recent years

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:09.820
as asylum authorities have been
more inclined to hear arguments

00:28:09.820 --> 00:28:12.650
that a social group
can be constituted

00:28:12.650 --> 00:28:17.130
around cultural practices,
beliefs and perceptions.

00:28:17.130 --> 00:28:19.290
This project also offers an avenue

00:28:19.290 --> 00:28:23.170
to investigate how
expertise is constituted

00:28:23.170 --> 00:28:26.640
and mobilized in legal settings.

00:28:26.640 --> 00:28:29.750
In the colonial cases
that I am examining,

00:28:29.750 --> 00:28:33.800
a category of intermediary,
native assessor,

00:28:33.800 --> 00:28:38.600 position:56%
typically men who were taken from
the local community that the parties

00:28:38.600 --> 00:28:44.640 position:56%
to the case belong to, operated as
interpreters of culture and language

00:28:44.640 --> 00:28:48.360
between the parties to the
case and British justices.

00:28:48.360 --> 00:28:50.760
They explained the
finer points of culture

00:28:50.760 --> 00:28:52.910
that were brought up in cases.

00:28:52.910 --> 00:28:56.520
They explained particular
vernacular terms.

00:28:56.520 --> 00:29:02.350
And they bona fide or denied the
participants in the case's claims

00:29:02.350 --> 00:29:06.290
about how culture operated
in their cases.

00:29:06.290 --> 00:29:08.880
So something that I
found very striking is

00:29:08.880 --> 00:29:12.980
that in asylum cases
today, social scientists,

00:29:12.980 --> 00:29:16.390
very often anthropologists,
serve in the role

00:29:16.390 --> 00:29:18.080
of a modern day native assessor.

00:29:18.080 --> 00:29:21.920
As expert witnesses, they
serve as intermediaries

00:29:21.920 --> 00:29:26.500
between the asylum claimants
and the asylum adjudicators

00:29:26.500 --> 00:29:28.600
who are hearing the cases.

00:29:28.600 --> 00:29:32.450
And they occupy many of the
same kinds of roles of cultural

00:29:32.450 --> 00:29:33.810
and linguistic translation.

00:29:33.810 --> 00:29:39.190
So some of the core questions that
I'm applying in doing this research

00:29:39.190 --> 00:29:43.180
and in writing it up
is in the question of,

00:29:43.180 --> 00:29:46.760
can the law effectively
intervene in witchcraft?

00:29:46.760 --> 00:29:51.490 position:56%
How is reasonableness constituted in
state courts and in asylum venues?

00:29:51.490 --> 00:29:58.320
And what are the limits of cultural
relativism in asylum settings?

00:29:58.320 --> 00:30:02.720
So I think that these cases
open up a lens through which

00:30:02.720 --> 00:30:08.080
to consider the really global
reach of local forms of violence.

00:30:08.080 --> 00:30:09.380
Thank you.

