and mentioned, which is this idea of
labels, definitions and categories.

00:30:28.690 --> 00:30:31.660
And that's something that we all
talked about amongst ourselves

00:30:31.660 --> 00:30:36.330
when we initially thought
up the idea for this event.

00:30:36.330 --> 00:30:39.980
And I believe it was Kate who
actually used this phrase,

00:30:39.980 --> 00:30:43.660
which I loved, which was the
bureaucratization of experiences

00:30:43.660 --> 00:30:45.130
into state-defined categories.

00:30:45.130 --> 00:30:47.060
Which is kind of a mouthful.

00:30:47.060 --> 00:30:50.360
But thinking about we
have people who are moving

00:30:50.360 --> 00:30:55.550
for all various reasons in
history from places to places.

00:30:55.550 --> 00:30:56.950
Sometimes we call them migrants.

00:30:56.950 --> 00:30:58.310
Sometimes we call them immigrants.

00:30:58.310 --> 00:31:00.060
Sometimes we call them refugees.

00:31:00.060 --> 00:31:02.290
Sometimes we call them
asylum seekers.

00:31:02.290 --> 00:31:07.620
And at each point, some body, some
state body, some governing body,

00:31:07.620 --> 00:31:11.430
some global body has to make a
definition and a designation.

00:31:11.430 --> 00:31:15.120
And each of you have come up
against this in your research.

00:31:15.120 --> 00:31:18.030
So maybe we could star
there and talk a little bit

00:31:18.030 --> 00:31:21.140
about these terminologies and
how they factor into the stories

00:31:21.140 --> 00:31:26.570
that you're uncovering and the
research that you're doing.

00:31:26.570 --> 00:31:27.870
&gt;&gt; Julia Young: Yeah.

00:31:27.870 --> 00:31:29.170
Well, your comment
just made me think

00:31:29.170 --> 00:31:34.960
about an interesting development in
the historical study of immigration

00:31:34.960 --> 00:31:38.080
which people may or may not
know about, which is, you know,

00:31:38.080 --> 00:31:40.250
in US immigration history --

00:31:40.250 --> 00:31:44.300
so the history of immigration
to the United States.

00:31:44.300 --> 00:31:49.820
One of the seminal, earliest
studies of migration is a book

00:31:49.820 --> 00:31:52.710
by Oscar Handlin called
The Uprooted.

00:31:52.710 --> 00:31:59.960 position:56%
And it presents this image of
migrants as people who are the poor,

00:31:59.960 --> 00:32:05.380
the downtrodden, people who are
uprooted from their local context

00:32:05.380 --> 00:32:12.900
and then flung into their new land
and forced to recollect themselves

00:32:12.900 --> 00:32:15.410
and reconstruct their lives.

00:32:15.410 --> 00:32:22.600
Essentially it treats immigrants
almost as handicapped people,

00:32:22.600 --> 00:32:25.720
people that are almost
a blank slate or people

00:32:25.720 --> 00:32:27.020
who are without a background.

00:32:27.020 --> 00:32:31.100
And the historiography on
immigration is changing

00:32:31.100 --> 00:32:32.900
and has changed over
the 20th century

00:32:32.900 --> 00:32:37.280
and it's increasingly recognizing
immigrants as people who come

00:32:37.280 --> 00:32:43.630
with a political context, who come
with a background of their own.

00:32:43.630 --> 00:32:45.630
And that they bring with them,

00:32:45.630 --> 00:32:47.900
that they don't leave
in their home country.

00:32:47.900 --> 00:32:49.370
They're not uprooted people.

00:32:49.370 --> 00:32:52.640
They might be transplanted people,
or there are other metaphors

00:32:52.640 --> 00:32:54.810
that people have come up with.

00:32:54.810 --> 00:32:58.330
And I think that's a
positive development,

00:32:58.330 --> 00:33:00.090
but I'm not sure it's translated

00:33:00.090 --> 00:33:02.040
into public discourse
on immigration.

00:33:02.040 --> 00:33:05.610
And I'm not sure it's translated
into the immigration courts, right?

00:33:05.610 --> 00:33:10.120
These are people with
a real understanding

00:33:10.120 --> 00:33:12.970
of the context which
immigrants left.

00:33:12.970 --> 00:33:14.610
So I'll stop there.

00:33:14.610 --> 00:33:18.640
&gt;&gt; Katherine Luongo: Yeah, I think
